Food blames European inflation
The main reason for the increase in inflation in the euro area is the rapidly rising food prices.
In the 13 countries of the eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November – after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, according to the EU Statistics Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have been set at just 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the leitzsins. At its discretion, the interest rate reduction would favour the rise in commodity prices and the slight fall in unemployment the emergence of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below two percent, or at least close to the two percent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the midst of a crisis: inflation must be “reciprocated” in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate climbed from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Rising food and energy prices are responsible for rising inflation in the euro area.
MATIF wheat quotations rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the price of edible oil and dairy products in 2007.
The world market price for crude oil rose 52 percent this year – last month, the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly $100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but is expected to fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts expect a 3 percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice.
Gallup is in the midst of a government crisis
After a long period of stagnation, the number of Fidesz supporters has grown considerably by the beginning of December, with the party having the largest base camp since 2002, while the approval of the Socialists has reached an unprecedented low of 13 percent, according to Gallup.
Among the party loyalists, the difference is clear thanks to the high determination of the opposition supporters: More than two-thirds (71 percent) are opposed to a fifth (20 percent) approval for the MSZP.
According to the survey, MDF and SZDSZ are below the parliamentary threshold: they reach two percent of the total population.
The number of party voters has grown by one percent in both camps.
Compared to the last low point, the general economic mood has continued to deteriorate – never before has the proportion of those who consider the country’s economic situation to be “pronounced bad” been so high (41 percent), while another 46 percent consider it to be “quite bad”.
After more hopeful prospects in spring and summer, families see the change in their financial situation again more pessimistic.
For the coming year, the majority of the population expects a further deterioration of the situation; only a tenth expects an improvement.
A Gallup poll conducted in December found that 71% of respondents – a historic high – rated the prime minister’s work as “rather bad than right.”
Thirteen percent of respondents have great confidence or confidence in Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny in general, while the share of supporters for Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n is 38 percent.
About 54% do not trust the head of government at all, compared to 27% distrust of the head of the Fidesz party.
One of the indicators of the political mood is the number of those who think that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister could be overcome even without a change of government.
If, after the unrest last October, 35% had spoken out for the stay of the government and the head of government, this share today amounts to only 20%, while the relative majority (33%) sees the solution only in new elections.
Asked about their interest in the referendum, 60 percent said they would “probably” participate, and another 20 percent would “probably” cast their vote.
For comparison, if the parliamentary elections were to take place this Sunday, only 55 percent would "certainly" go to the polls, another 15 percent would consider their participation "probably". Given these trends, the result of the referendum would be predictable.
74% would vote against the tuition fees, 79% against the practice fee, and 84% against the hospital day allowance.
The share of the opponents of the study, practice and hospital fees would be 81, 84, and 89 percent, respectively, of the group of participants "with certainty" in the referendum.
