Disinfectants are saved in many places
This year, more than a thousand infections were registered in hospitals due to improper use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not exactly conducive to the containment of infections, according to the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The victim of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly afterwards the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation could not be carried out because of the bacterium that is still in the patient's body.
Until December 10, 1094 infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens were reported from hospitals to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, the lead physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals for sure, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium carries about a third of the people in its nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, tonsillitis, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the agents are dosed too high or used improperly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria are formed from the well-responsible bacteria, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune systems, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause serious infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of everyday hospital life.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA only does not exist where it is not sought.
Resistant to antibiotics
"Such patients are being isolated, the nursing staff is wearing rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
When they are admitted to the hospital, the patients are examined for MRSA, but an infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances are unfavorable for the containment of the emergence or spread of the multiresistant pathogen, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
After this infection occurs predominantly in hospitals and nursing homes, the hospitals should examine the delivered patients and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
In Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no grants for this study from the state health fund.
Most cases will therefore only come to light if the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
On the part of the European Union, there are strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and disease images.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, that is, microbiological tests are necessary so that no resistance to the drug can be formed, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer among outpatients or patients in primary care, according to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Saved by Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to the other by caregivers.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also significant shortcomings in this area in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted through droplet infection or contact, but there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patient in the local hospitals.
The rooms are even often overcrowded, the beds barely lined up, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz further notes, unfortunately, in the less well-off hospitals, it even happens that disinfectants are spared, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that directly favor the emergence of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped, where these protective measures are observed, according to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Government program against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections under control causes the health insurance companies enormous costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government program.
According to initial indications, the program is successful - as published data show, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the emergence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
