Bulgaria, the real estate paradise of the EU
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is fabulous - the whole of Europe is paying attention to the previously rarely mentioned Balkan state.
What, where, and who buys in the EU’s still cheapest market, but which is rapidly becoming more expensive?
An analysis of the Bulgarian Re/Max Division.
Bulgaria is currently without a doubt the most sought-after patch for property purchases in the Eastern European area, with cheap ski apartments and houses by the sea.
Among the mountains, the regions of Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa are among the most popular, on the sea are Albena, the "gold coast", the "sun coast", and the historic towns of Sozopol and Nessebar the riders, however, properties around Kavarna and Balcik are also increasingly in demand.
According to estimates of Re/Max analysts in Bulgaria wid also the interior of the country sooner or later attract investors, such as Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, and Triavna, and also the highly favorable area of Russia recorded more buyers.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive offers - commercial and office spaces offer the highest returns.
Bulgaria is on the best way to become one of the most attractive European golfing paradises, and thus, in addition to the summer and winter seasons, also attract tourists in the other two seasons.
Predictive investors are therefore already buying in on a large scale, for example around Bansko.
According to analysts, people who buy real estate in Bulgaria also seek a change in their lifestyle.
Most buyers are English, but there are also interested people from France, Belgium, Spain, and more and more from Romania.
Investors from Malta and Cyprus are also present, while there are mainly Russian buyers at the Black Sea and in the ski resorts.
There are three groups of foreign buyers, says Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
Those who want to settle down buy either revitalized properties by 50-100,000 euros, or demolished houses by 5-15,000 euros, which they then renovate themselves.
Good connectivity and accessibility as well as communication possibilities are greatly written, but also the proximity to a major city, shops and doctors are crucial for the buyers.
The second category includes those who are looking for a holiday home (Bulgaria was listed among the top ten holiday destinations of the Germans in December).
The third group consists of business people who invest with the aim of medium to long-term value increase.
However, real estate in the capital is becoming more and more expensive due to ever-increasing demand.
Within the EU, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria, but in the last five years there has been a price increase of 21 percent annually.
The cost of property prices far exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian Six Percents
As Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali Roadmap, which sets out emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a fierce debate going on between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that it does not want to negotiate concrete figures, but would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other big question of the conference is whether the industrialized countries are ready to support the developing countries, in addition to reducing emissions, both financially and technologically.
An agreement on assistance to developing countries was also reached.
The Adaptation Fund, which is subject to the Kyoto Protocol, is to be managed by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be read in the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as in the "Piac és Profit".
Hungary's 6 percent
Environment Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU’s efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate action and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said that by 2020, the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "after 2012 agreement" will be achieved successfully or not. The Union would even be willing to commit to a 30% reduction if other major industrial states of the world, or developing countries, are also ready to comply with their commitments.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor stressed that the objective of the states that had acceded to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 percent, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its then 15 member states.
