The commitment is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not come into force until after 2012, in which case the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new, international emission reduction system, the IPCC, the International Peace Prize, with its significance.
This would delay the emission reduction, and an increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British Army advertises on YouTube
British Army units have published footage of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in order to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) has discovered YouTube for itself: Special forces stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reports.
The camera footage, which is mounted on helmets, is checked at the Kandahar Air Force Base and then sent to London, where it is placed on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos about Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Foreign Office (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces (MNFI) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force released the videos with the goal of recruiting soldiers, and as the Ministry of Defense says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual goals of foreign operations.
This kind of propaganda is almost free compared to conventional television commercials, according to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, but these videos always carry a certain amount of political message, since they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur footage, which, in addition to carefully edited, censored footage, also creates a net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: in the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, the losses are talked about at most, but the bloody sides of the war are not mentioned.
By the way, numerous videos have already been uploaded to the platform from the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British have only recently discovered this "species".
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free-to-download shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-saving simulation.
