Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated precisely by law, so that the practice of rescheduling working days around the holidays has now become established, but the coming year will give us fewer such days.
Even in the EU and in America, something else is understood as "holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and non-working days.
Unemployed days are usually church holidays, or are associated with significant historical events.
For example, we also celebrate the New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are work-free days - the last day alone so that the New Year's Eve celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state holidays are the 15th of March, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August the foundation of the state is celebrated, on the 1st of May the work is celebrated, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each for Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national, or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of “working day shift” has proven successful in cases where we would work just one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before that, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, for many years the Minister of Labour has set out in his own regulation.
The legislation applies to all employers and employers, public employees and civil servants alike.
Exceptions are only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
This year, the working order is only somewhat confused by the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24th, life in this country remains formally standing, since most people take time off for the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve, or the holiday specifically cancelled for this purpose.
Next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or to the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redundancies on working days than this year.
The calendar is first "turned on its head" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days at a time.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day, so Friday, May 2 can be a day of rest.
The second rearrangement is related to the holiday on October 23: on Saturday, October 18, you will have to work in advance on Friday, October 24.
The end of the year, however, will be marked by the holidays, after everything has been lying and standing since December 24, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
Six Disturbing Little Things to annoy Working Colleagues
Emails that we forget to send, voice messages that we never receive - harmless lies that we no longer notice: they bring "color" into everyday life in the workplace.
The only question is whether you get used to these little inconveniences, or you better face the challenge and try to avoid these misunderstandings, for other annoying situations consciously.
Tips.
"Sorry, I forgot to point out that someone called from the marketing department," says a colleague.
Did you miss a meeting?
At best, you regret it and try to make it right again by perhaps calling the marketing department and humbly admitting that you had forgotten to align the message (this is the less common method).
Most of the time, it is done with an apology.
Before getting caught up in embarrassing excuses, you should consider how you can really prepare your colleagues for unpleasant moments and try to consciously avoid these situations.
Borrow something that doesn’t belong to you?
There’s hardly anything more nerve-wracking than reaching for a document, office supplies, or the phone, but it’s not there.
Yesterday the stapler was still on the desk - this morning it's gone?
Or is the lost ballpoint pen discovered on a colleague’s desk?
Without asking, one should not borrow anything from colleagues, because they are rightly annoyed when they find that something has gone away.
So, do not put envelopes or post-it out of the office in your pocket, because it could hit you yourself: no more there, if you need it urgently.
Talking about the privacy of your colleagues?
There is no effective way to stop a trachea that has already been put into the world.
Who did what with whom?
Where and why?
You should not tie the information (or assumptions) about the privacy of colleagues to everyone's nose if possible!
And if someone opens up and reveals his innermost secret to us, we should not abuse this trust!
It is best to remain silent like a grave, rather than aligning with those who are not present, even if others are aware of the problems of the colleague.
Reported ill for no reason?
When you call in the office to report sick, citing painful headaches, because you are feeling uncomfortable, or just want to rest, you should be clear about one thing: your own work, unremitting achievements, projects with fixed deadlines must now be done by your colleagues instead of yourself.
Don’t play with your colleagues!
If you already know the day before that you will not be able to put it in the office the next day, or that something could get in the way, so you have to stay at home, you should report it in time so that neither the colleagues nor the boss are unexpectedly confronted with the absence.
summaries, jokes, phone calls
You are in the depths of your work, but are suddenly disturbed by the loud whims of your colleagues?
Unintentionally listening to a phone call that you shouldn’t have heard better?
You should not annoy your colleagues with buzzing, singing, loud conversations (which you carry across their heads), trampling, constant snarling or tingling.
All this can be very disturbing, even if they are not deep in one task (writing, planning, organizing).
Are the others always to blame?
If a project is not ready on time, you have to forget to send an important letter or important messages, you should not look for the fault of your own forgetfulness in others!
If possible, do not talk about the chaos in the office or the loud colleagues!
It is best to admit your mistakes, and apologize if others have been affected by them!
The question of how to correct the mistake again, or catch up with the missed one, is just too appropriate!
In the office - a feeling like home?
Training pants and slippers: Comfortable for home, but has lost nothing in the office!
Not even then one should dress so casually if the workplace would actually allow it!
Just don't get too slutty - you should respect both your colleagues and yourself to the extent that you dress appropriately in the office - if desired, also pretty and elegant!
