Banks want to deal with the crisis
The US Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the central banks of Great Britain, Switzerland and Canada have decided to fight together against the crisis in the financial markets.
More than $100 billion will go to the currency markets through auctions.
At these auctions, banks auction interest rates at which they are willing to lend each other money.
For example, the U.S. Fed is sending $40 billion at auction, with another 24 making it loose for the European and Swiss central banks.
It is the first time since the September 11 attacks that the central banks of each state have agreed on such a coordinated approach to fend off or mitigate the consequences of a financial crisis.
"This step is intended to eliminate the greatest difficulties facing the economy, i.e. the increasing lack of freely available capital that banks can lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in a report for his clients.
"The coordinated action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65% to about 50%," Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to non-performing loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect billions more to be lost.
“The central banks must have been really afraid of what could happen if they decided to do it,” said Kieran Davies, chief economist at ABN Amro.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he continued.
Central banks are concerned that if banks themselves have difficult access to bonds, loans will also become more expensive for their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession, potentially impacting economic growth around the world.
The central banks have decided to lower the LIBOR, the London interbank interest rate used for interbank lending, after failing to do so.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend each other money, even though the central banks of the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom had lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further lowering of interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts believe that this step by central banks contributes to the warming of the crisis, because it does not solve the fundamental problem, namely the case of the real estate market in the United States.
