Cuba - the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Whatever you expect from your holiday will be fulfilled if you choose only the right one.
Golden and white beaches, high waves or a sea that is quiet like a pond.
Palm trees and All Inclusive with waiters offering pizza, ice cream and bewitching cocktails on the beach.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean you will find this to an excessive extent.
Only on one island you will find much more, and this island is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful of the Great Antilles.
At the time of the Spanish, Cuba was their bastion for the conquest of America.
Columbus called it the most beautiful place a human eye has ever seen.
Havana once became a camp or transit camp of treasures that the Spaniards had stolen in America and then transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was founded at the end of the 20th century.
It was built by one of the leaders of the American mafia, Lucky Luciano, because everything that was considered a crime in the United States (especially during prohibition) was liked and supported in Cuba - drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his guests were, among others.
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rises grew, across the broad boulevards were cars that were among the iconic symbols of the 1950s.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Coj<0xC3><0xAD>mar he had his yacht lying.
On the walls of Bodeguita del Medio, stars of the show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures.
And today?
You can also leave your autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita of Havana.
Cocktails can be mixed at the bar at Hotel Nacional.
And the cult cars of the fifties still drive around in Havana to this day, because the once imported schigulis and fiats have long since fallen apart in the salty and moist air.
While Havana, especially its oldest part, may have come down heavily, nowhere can you find as many wonderful colonial sights as right here.
Other places are being cleaned up, such as Trinidad.
In view of the fact that tourism brings urgently needed money, there was a green light for this development.
In the last fifteen years, not only in Havana, new hotels have been created, but also in Varadero, on the coast of the province of Holgu<0xC3><0xAD>n and also on islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a marotte that is unique in the world and especially attracts railway lovers.
The sugar cane from remote plantations brought steam and diesel-powered narrow gauge railways to the sugar factories.
Their fleet has not been renewed for decades, and so you can see clean and fully functioning locomotives, whose peers have been in the museum for a long time.
Excursion destinations
The most important places do not exclude the majority of visitors to Cuba.
So you don’t have to write about Varadero or Havana in detail anymore.
It remains only to mention that there is a museum in the already mentioned estate of Hemingways, whose visit should not be missed by the one who likes this writer.
The Vi<0xC3><0xB1>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
The lush vegetation grows on lime soil.
The mogotas, limestone hills and rocks, protrude steeply from the valley floor, in their cavities fertile soil accumulated, through which even weathered rock areas are covered with dense vegetation.
This valley is where perhaps the best Cuban tobacco is grown.
In its final form, you can meet it when you visit one of Havana’s cigar factories.
It may also seem interesting to some that the Chilean episode of the television series "Major Zeman" was filmed there.
Trinidad
An ancient city that was founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
Her fame and wealth brought her the trade in slaves and sugar.
The wealth was embodied in the beautiful beauty of the small town.
The Spanish colonial architecture, strongly influenced by the later French settlers, has hardly changed in the last four hundred years.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the Escambray Mountains, is a place so remote that there was no road connecting the area with the rest of the country in the 1950s.
This isolation helped to keep it unattended.
Nothing was built there, but therefore nothing was torn down, everyone was glad that he had a roof over his head.
If you have more than one afternoon for Trinidad, then it is worth looking at interesting places in the area, such as Playa Anc<0xC3><0xB3>n beach or the "Valley of Sugar Factories".
In the evening you should then go to the Casa de la M<0xC3><0xBA>sica, which revives after dark, and where the music does not remain silent until the morning.
Baracoa
This small town in eastern Cuba is considered by some to be the most beautiful on the island.
Certainly, this view is also influenced by the way there.
Both roads leading from Guant<0xC3><0xA1>namo have to overcome high and rugged mountains and run through a landscape barely touched by human intervention.
This eastern outpost of Cuba was listed by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site thanks to its unspoiled nature.
There the best chocolate is made, in the church you can see the cross of Columbus (in fact, it was created about a hundred years after the voyages of Columbus), and from the hill where the former castle, the current hotel El Castillo, there are several table mountains, of which El Yunque is the most famous.
About the coffee, the rum, the cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountains, the bay of pigs and the island of Isla de Pinos, about the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the Cuban patron Caridad del Cobre, about the Santeria, an African religion, to which the descendants of slaves confess, you could write many pages about all this.
But, as they say, it is better to look with your own eyes.
