Bush calls for agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
At the opening of the international peace conference, which met Tuesday under his leadership in Annapolis, Maryland, President Bush announced that Israelis and Palestinians had finally agreed to a joint declaration.
He further stated that Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to immediately begin negotiations to find a final settlement of the 60-year-old disputes between their two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, Bush promised that he would do everything possible to help them conclude a peace treaty before the end of 2008.
In the meantime, the Palestinians must destroy the terrorist infrastructure and Israel must stop its colonization work, Bush said, reminding the two parties of their commitments to the peace roadmap they had agreed to in 2003.
The head of the White House stressed that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority under Abbas ultimately seek a peace treaty that would clarify all open issues without exception, and including the central issues.
This term encompasses the three serious problems that have been the main focus of Israeli-Palestinian disputes: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees who were expelled from their homeland in the 1948 conflict in what is now the State of Israel.
According to the American president, Abbas took the floor and insisted that the upcoming negotiations be conducted comprehensively and thoroughly and provide a settlement for all points, including Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water and security.
When Olmert took the floor for his part, he pledged that the upcoming ceasefire negotiations would be conducted directly and without interruption and that he would make every effort to ensure that they could be concluded before the end of 2008.
Bush has set the deadline for the implementation of his vision of two states, one Palestinian and one Israeli, which will exist side by side, by the end of 2008.
Saudi Arabia has revealed that it has received assurances from Bush in this sense before deciding to attend the conference.
Arabia, whose participation in Annapolis represents a great success for Washington, has pioneered a plan adopted by all Arab countries that offers Israel peace, in exchange for its withdrawal from all Arab territories that had been occupied during the 1967 war, including East Jerusalem.
Annapolis represents a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and its central points of view, the Saudi prince says in his interview with the Saudi-funded Arabic-language daily newspaper.
