Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and his companions from the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) will have taken more than seven hours in space to perform the spectacular repair of a faulty solar collector, which is indispensable for the continuation of scientific work on the station.
A daring exit that has achieved several records due to its duration, the removal of habitable modules, the speed with which it was organized, and the tools built by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem occurred on Wednesday when the astronauts had unloaded the Harmony module from the space shuttle Discovery, a large cylindrical part that is soon to take up the European and Japanese scientific laboratories.
This module is a kind of landing bridge for the module laboratories.
But you have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to implement a 17.5-tonne module for generating electricity via solar collectors, which was already on the ISS, in order to bring it to its final position.
After moving it, the crew decided to restructure the solar panels of the module, the span of which is 76 meters.
And it happened that one of the collectors, which can be unfolded like accordions, was damaged by a clamped cable on a length of about one meter.
The restructuring was stopped in order not to damage the collector even more.
The astronauts, who were originally to leave the space shuttle Discovery for a control walk and then repair another solar collector whose rotation system was faulty, were forced to dedicate themselves to the damaged collector.
And Scott Parazynski was selected to walk around at the end of the space shuttle’s 30-meter-long remote-controlled arm, which had been attached to the station, to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA’s best spacewalkers.
Large, resistant, very skillful, he has a well-developed upper body and long arms.
The 46-year-old learned doctor was thus selected to operate the injured solar collector.
After carefully inspecting the damage, he severed the faulty cable and attached some kind of rail to the damaged area.
He was supported by a second Spacewalker who stayed near the lock, and, from inside, by the other astronauts, among them Peggy Whitson, commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick, wrapped with insulator to prevent an electric shock on the solar collectors, which generate several hundred volts, had been designed and built by the astronauts aboard the station.
When the action was over, Scott Parazynski waited for the collector to fully unfold before counting down his tools and returning to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed half a day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the space shuttle Discovery, expected to take the return flight to Earth on Wednesday.
