“It is an honor for our company to work with a person who has served, no more and no less, as a role model for the current festival movement in America,” said Charlie Jones of C3 on Billboard.com.
C3 hosts the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
Vineland, New Jersey, is a summer destination for camping holidays.
The festival will probably take place from August 8-10 on a 500 acre private farm about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
Festival Republic director Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the producers of the world’s most prestigious festivals.
In 1989, he took over the management of the Reading Festival in the United Kingdom, which attracts around 80,000 people annually.
In 1999, Melvin Benn added the Leeds Festival to his portfolio, and then, in 2006, Festival Republic created the Latitude Festival in Henham Park, Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn, in his capacity as co-owner, has also taken care of the production, licensing and organisational tasks of the Glastonbury Festival, which can now accommodate up to 177,500 people.
Charlie Jones of C3, who describes Glastonbury as the most inspiring event he’s ever attended, says his company and Melvin Benn’s are working side-by-side to offer the area a European-style festival event.
We have selected Philadelphia as a market and are working diligently with the Fairmount Park Commission to create a festival in downtown Philadelphia, says Charlie Jones.
We held negotiations with the city and the Commission was motivated and enthusiastic about this project.
Unfortunately, we are stuck in political debates regarding the current administration, continues Charlie Jones.
"Fortunately, we were able to discuss with Melvin Benn and we are making preparations to create a great festival in an extraordinary place that will ultimately benefit the population."
C3 Presents brought the 2005 Lollapalooza Festival to life in Grand Park Chicago after it joined the Austin City Limits Music Festival in 2002.
The two events each earned $9.8 million and $11.8 million in gross tax days in 2007.
These two festivals take place in an urban environment.
“The European model of Melvin Benn is a rural festival, whereas ours are more likely to take place on the urban green spaces,” says Charlie Jones.
“The goal is to merge these two concepts in one way or another to simultaneously convey the impression of a rural festival on the European and an urban one in the American way.”
Vineland is approximately halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“The community of Vineland, including the Mayor, is taking the burden of this event with joy,” says Charlie Jones.
The latter refuses to disclose the terms of the agreement, but he confirms that "they are interesting enough to invest in such an event and host a festival that hopefully will have a long life."
Charlie Jones says the festival’s recording capacity is “very large,” corresponding to about 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo Music Festival in Tennessee.
He says the invitations have been sent to the groups, but that nothing could be confirmed when they were printed.
“Vineland will offer tasteful rock, but the music will be very diverse, hoping to attract all kinds of audiences,” says Charlie Jones.
