The recommendation by Chief Financial Controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought in conjunction with the Glasgow airport attack in June.
Black also expressed concerns that the Scottish State Health Service has no precise idea of the number of its foreign employees.
But his report pointed out that other important controls were correctly performed on a sample of five health authorities.
The chief financial controller investigated staff recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a SUV was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video broadcast at Old Bailey in October, and was charged in connection with the alleged car bomb attack in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out pre-employment checks on foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorisations to work in the UK.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to review criminal records, the agency does not have the jurisdiction to obtain this information outside the UK.
The auditor’s report now states, among other recommendations, that the board should take up guidelines of the criminal record extract, which helps employers with checks in different countries.
"Although we found evidence of these controls in some personnel records, these were not routinely performed," the report noted.
Black said the Scottish health authorities would follow their pre-employment screening guidelines to a high degree, but added: "Our report shows areas where the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information about the number of foreign health workers is available."
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations in advance of hiring potential NHS staff would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that NHS Scotland's current pre-employment tests are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number is likely to be higher, also because the boards would have problems identifying those employees who are on indefinite leave.
The investigation further found that established control procedures by NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian had been predominantly complied with.
This includes passport, work permit, and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing its pre-employment screening policies and guidelines for foreign staff in the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "It was a concern of mine to carry out this work in the face of the Glasgow Airport terrorist attack."
She added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health authorities, would take into account the report’s recommendations and ensure that best practices are reflected in updated guidance on pre-employment screenings for all employees – including those from abroad – which are scheduled to be released next month.
