The climate on Venus could reveal a view of the future of the Earth
Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft on orbit show that the planet is even more like a distant twin of the Earth than previously thought.
Venus is the closest planetary neighbor to Earth.
The two worlds are about the same size and have similar planetary orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the sun.
Billions of years ago there would have been conditions on Venus that would have been very similar to those on Earth and could even have been habitable, scientists believe today.
But because of the unbridled carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, the erosion of the atmosphere by solar radiation and a slower rotation rate, Venus took a completely different course of development.
Today, the planet is devoid of water and has a surface temperature that is hot enough to melt lead and is devastated by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency’s Venus Express spacecraft, which has been studying the plants for a year, provide a sobering glimpse into how Earth could evolve in the face of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor of the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford, one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said: “It becomes clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, while the planets are otherwise quite similar.”
“Our new data will allow us to construct a scenario in which Venus started billions of years ago like Earth, possibly with a habitable environment.”
