The pain of the Labour Party
Gordon Brown has discovered yet another pit to fall into; his way out of it remains the same.
For British scandals, this is not particularly flattering.
No titles of nobility seem to have been sold, no politicians paid Parisian hotel bills, no extra-marital toes have been squandered.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman has been hiding donations for the British ruling Labour Party over more than <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 ($1.3 million) over four years under the name of other people, and that the party has failed to report this, is something that the rival Gordon Brown would have done well without.
When two months ago the Prime Minister had evaded the demand for an election, in a foolish way insulting the intelligence of the British by claiming that opinion polls had not influenced this decision, there was hope that he would offer a robust, efficient government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the increasingly sharp-witted chairman of the Liberal Democrats, put it, the once-feared Brown from Stalin has evolved into Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of Northern Rock, a battered bank, showed regulatory weakness and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change tax laws have brought corporate associations against the government.
The tax authorities’ loss of personal data of 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative pfusheries.
A trio of retired generals launched an uprising in the upper house in protest at cuts in military spending: to be a minister of the armed forces, they claimed, was a part-time job.
Now there are the diverse donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary general (and her former fulfillment manager) has already resigned.
None of this means that Brown is irrevocably heading for retirement.
Yet governments can reach a turning point after which they find it impossible to govern.
Neither like nor trust politicians, but they usually hold back their skepticism when a new troupe takes office.
Once it is clear that it is unlikely that a prime minister will improve the situation, and he does not even have to be there for a long time, this delay is over: the public service is starting to run away; the cabinet ministers are starting to chat; the press is looking for bad news; and the government is becoming defensive and aimless.
In a way, Brown’s position is particularly difficult because, unlike other political leaders, he cannot claim to be a new broom.
As much as he would deny Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant.
The problems with Northern Rock and the tax filings, for example, are related to decisions that Brown made as Chancellor of the Treasury.
And even if he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s misdeeds — as in the long “money for titles” investigation of political party funding — voters may assume he was.
Still, Brown's situation isn't quite as bad as it looks
The offenses are not as terrible as the Conservatives describe them.
As with Mr. Bean, no one has died, or been completely scammed.
And the antidote, painful as it may be, is to deliver what Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, solid and slightly brutal government.
The new gesture of political donations is a good example.
The garboesque of Abraham, who compares his donations to his charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
That may be the case, but the decision was not up to him.
The anti-anonymity laws for large political contributors are clear and they exist for a clear reason: the public has a right to know who can buy access to those who rule the country.
Watt, who says he knew about Abraham’s deal but didn’t know it was illegal, will of course have to ask himself some questions; just like Jon Mendlesohn, Labour’s chief financial driver, who was told about the strange donations in October.
But so far Brown is not involved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these confusions, although most of the payments were made after his inauguration in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He quickly condemned the violation of the laws by his party, but he watered down this determination by grabbing a known instrument, a committee of inquiry on the subject - to make the measure full, from a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the "teachings to be drawn from them" are not very complicated.
If the law is broken, it is a matter for the police.
Apart from that, there are other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as find a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has been unoccupied for six months, and move forward with a comprehensive reform of political party funding.
That would require the hardliners of the Labour Party to cooperate with the Conservatives and possibly give up the special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a party comrade like Mr Brown.
But he should be aware of some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a clear lead in opinion polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way he can achieve victory is through unquestionable righteousness and solid competence.
