Is the credit crisis affecting the U.S. credit card market?
When blood is in the water, it is only natural that the back fins swirl excitedly.
Now that America’s real estate market is crumbling, the predators are targeting the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs expect credit card losses to reach $99 billion if the risk of under-funded credit spreads to other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of tension are clearly visible.
There are increases in both withdrawals and rescheduling rates, which measure the proportion of loans that are ineligible or more than 30 days too late.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken a $1.4 billion fee levy out of its U.S. consumer finance, in part because of the weakness of credit card holders.
However, it is too early to panic.
Losses and sneezes are still low.
According to Moody’s, the third-quarter seed rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
An amendment to the U.S. Private Insolvency Laws in 2005 resulted in an abrupt case of bankruptcy filings, which in turn account for a large portion of kedit card losses; the number of filings (and thus tuition fees) would rise again, whether the general conditions for borrowers worsen or not.
Industry also reports solid payment rates that show how much of their debt consumers pay off each month
and the trust in credit card-based securities is quite strong, despite the stalemate in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research company, expects that 2007 spending will ultimately be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct infection channels between the real estate credit crisis and the credit card market: consumers are more likely to take on credit card debt now that home loans are drying out.
However, card issuers look at the cash flow rather than capital values, so falling house prices do not necessarily trigger a change in the borrower’s creditworthiness.
They can even be of benefit to card issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue to pay mortgage rates fall when real estate is worth less than the value of the loan; as a result, card debt becomes more important under repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond much faster and more flexibly than lenders to the more stormy conditions by changing interest rates or credit limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risk of a rapid reassessment of assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and completely reassess the loans,” says Gary Perlin, Capital One’s chief financial officer.
Even if a sudden undercover crisis in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustainable downturn are considerably more real.
If lower house prices and a credit crunch push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a grimer future.
