British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who were due to stand trial for their role in the fraudulent system with Enron’s former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their pleas in guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven cases of fraud involving telecommunications means for allegedly conspiring with Fastow in a secret financial fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employer.
The procedure was set for January.
But during a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Junior, everyone pleaded guilty to a case of fraud using telecommunications means.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, were known in the UK in the course of extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, her case is a loose end to an investigation that began after Enron's collapse in 2001.
