At the beginning of 2002, the bank had estimated the value of its stake in the subsidiary at zero, but the three British men knew that it actually had significant value.
A company under Kopper’s control acquired the bank’s shares in the subsidiary for $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow misrepresented to Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in fact, the 20 million dollars went to the British bankers, Fastow and others.
