Hopes that the central bank will lower interest rates will lead to a rise in global equity markets
Stocks jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday, after market hopes that the central bank will try to calm credit markets by further lowering interest rates were bolstered by reassuring comments from the vice president of the U.S. central bank.
Stock markets rose in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kahn, the No. 2 of Ben Bernanke, the chairman of the central bank, said the policy had to respond “flexibly and pragmatically” to the ongoing pressure on the financial markets.
In a clear effort to calm troubled markets, given signs of rising credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turbulence had "partially reversed some of the improvements in market functions from the late part of September and October."
If the increased turbulence persists, it would increase the possibility of further tightening financial conditions for consumers and businesses, he said.
