Venus is the Earth's twin.
Despite its life-threatening atmosphere, Venus is more similar to Earth than previously thought: the European spacecraft "Venus Express" has detected lightning in the atmosphere and wind vortices at the poles, as they also occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that there is lightning on Venus.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided the evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "Ursuppen theory", lightning has created life on Earth: thunderstorms are said to have stimulated reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there ever was life there, it must have been in very early history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there is hardly anything living on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the devil’s twin on Earth, but she’s a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar in mass and size to Earth, has made such a completely different development, is the basic question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone for Venus research, as since the beginning of the nineties no more probes specifically for the exploration of this planet were underway.
The latest research results, which are now presented in several "Nature" articles, not only underscore the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system, according to the researchers.
"They also show that the similarities between our neighboring planet and Earth are greater than initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of air currents in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second-tallest planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is about the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as the morning or evening star, orbits the sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus barely resembles Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets were created under very similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated, which remained on Earth in oceans, but on Venus was lost to space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed in carbonaceous rocks on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
