These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you connect the terms Sweden and wooden box, think of IKEA, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden boxes manufactured in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol’s work directory.
A large part of the ninety-four Brillo boxes listed there from the "Typ Stockholm" are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago has cast doubt on the authenticity of Andy Warhol's works of art from the year 1968 onwards, internal research at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now come to a sobering conclusion: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which are the former museum director Pontus Hultén's works of art from 1995 onwards.
Prehistory is nestled, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "brillo boxes" in New York City, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard boxes of the "brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, exhibited hundreds of cardboard Brillo boxes: these did not come from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but their models, mere pieces of exhibition.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not, however, on display at the Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which at the time were authorized as original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm" rightfully entered into the history of art and auctions.
Some of them have earned more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem is now that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that there were about a hundred wooden boxes produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén’s 105 boxes were only produced in 1990 in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, Chief Conservator at the Moderna Museet, has also examined three privately owned Swedish Brillo boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press chip plates were first ground and lubricated, after which white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the copies from 1990, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the pressing chipboard with a paint roller without primer - in addition, it is not oil paint, but acrylic paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," Moderna Museum Director Lars Nittve states: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to a different conclusion, the Moderna Museum will copy the six classic boxes into its collection."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the “serious allegations” that are being raised in relation to the soap powder boxes.
Since then, however, there has been an inexorable silence.
